const bodyContent = `<div class="distance-bar">
  📍 Best Western Vernal Inn · 1935 South 1500 East, Vernal, UT — Your base for everything in the Uintah Basin
</div>

<div class="pbar">
  <div class="pi"><span class="ic">🦕</span><div><div class="label">~20 Min Drive</div><div class="sub">Dinosaur National Monument</div></div></div>
  <div class="pi"><span class="ic">🏞️</span><div><div class="label">~40 Min Drive</div><div class="sub">Flaming Gorge Reservoir</div></div></div>
  <div class="pi"><span class="ic">🦶</span><div><div class="label">~12 Min Drive</div><div class="sub">Red Fleet State Park</div></div></div>
  <div class="pi"><span class="ic">🪨</span><div><div class="label">~15 Min Drive</div><div class="sub">McConkie Ranch Petroglyphs</div></div></div>
  <div class="pi"><span class="ic">🏛️</span><div><div class="label">~5 Min Drive</div><div class="sub">Utah Field House Museum</div></div></div>
  <div class="pi"><span class="ic">⛳</span><div><div class="label">~5 Min Drive</div><div class="sub">Dinaland Golf Course</div></div></div>
</div>

<div class="content-wrap">

  <div class="intro-pull">
    Vernal, Utah is one of the most underrated adventure destinations in the American West — and most people only scratch the surface. Within 40 minutes of your hotel you have <strong>Dinosaur National Monument</strong>, <strong>Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area</strong>, <strong>Red Fleet State Park</strong>, ancient petroglyphs, world-class fishing, and some of the most dramatic canyon scenery in Utah. This is your complete guide to making the most of it.
  </div>

  <!-- DINOSAUR NATIONAL MONUMENT -->
  <section class="content-section rv">
    <h2>Dinosaur National Monument — The Crown Jewel (~20 Min)</h2>
    <p>No trip to Vernal is complete without visiting <strong>Dinosaur National Monument</strong>. The Quarry Exhibit Hall houses the famous Carnegie Quarry wall — a tilted sandstone slab with over 1,500 dinosaur bones left exactly where they were found. It is one of the most extraordinary fossil sites on Earth, and it is only 20 miles from your hotel.</p>
    <p>Beyond the quarry, the monument spans 210,000 acres of canyon country straddling the Utah-Colorado border. The Harpers Corner Scenic Drive delivers some of the most dramatic canyon views in the American West, while the Green River and Yampa River corridors draw rafters, kayakers, and hikers from across the country.</p>
    <ul class="feat-list">
      <li>Carnegie Quarry wall — 1,500+ visible dinosaur bones</li>
      <li>Harpers Corner Scenic Drive — 31 miles of canyon views</li>
      <li>Green River and Yampa River rafting</li>
      <li>Petroglyphs and ancient rock art panels</li>
      <li>Hiking trails for all skill levels</li>
      <li>Junior Ranger program for kids</li>
      <li>Certified Dark Sky Park — world-class stargazing</li>
      <li>Wildlife viewing — bighorn sheep, eagles, mule deer</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="pro-tip">
      <p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Arrive at the Quarry Exhibit Hall before 10 AM in summer — the shuttle from the parking area fills up fast and wait times can exceed 45 minutes by midday. Check <a href="https://www.nps.gov/dino" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--gold);font-weight:700">nps.gov/dino</a> for current hours and entry fees.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FLAMING GORGE -->
  <section class="content-section rv">
    <h2>Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area (~40 Min)</h2>
    <p>Flaming Gorge is a 91-mile reservoir carved through dramatic red-rock canyons on the Utah-Wyoming border — and one of the most visually stunning places in the entire state. The water is a brilliant blue-green against rust-colored canyon walls, and the recreation options are nearly endless year-round.</p>
    <p>Drive the <strong>Flaming Gorge–Uintas National Scenic Byway</strong> south from Vernal on US-191 — the drive itself is worth the trip. Stop at the dam overlook, rent a boat at Lucerne Valley Marina, or hike the canyon rim trails above the gorge.</p>
    <div class="attraction-cards">
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>🎣 Trophy Fishing</strong>
        <p>Lake trout, smallmouth bass, and kokanee salmon. One of the top fishing destinations in the entire West.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>🚤 Boating &amp; Kayaking</strong>
        <p>Boat rentals and marinas at Lucerne Valley and Antelope Flat. 91 miles of reservoir to explore.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>🥾 Rim Hiking</strong>
        <p>Canyon rim trails with jaw-dropping views of the gorge. Red Canyon Visitor Center is a must-stop.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>🏕️ Camping</strong>
        <p>Multiple campgrounds along the reservoir — from full hookups to primitive riverside sites.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RED FLEET & PETROGLYPHS -->
  <section class="content-section rv">
    <h2>Red Fleet State Park &amp; McConkie Ranch Petroglyphs</h2>
    <p><strong>Red Fleet State Park</strong> is one of those places most visitors drive right past — and that is a mistake. The park features a beautiful blue-green reservoir set against dramatic red sandstone formations, a well-preserved dinosaur tracksite accessible by a short hike or kayak, and some of the best swimming in the Uintah Basin. It is only 10 miles north of Vernal.</p>
    <p>Just 15 minutes west of Vernal, the <strong>McConkie Ranch Petroglyph Trail</strong> winds through a canyon lined with some of the finest Fremont-era rock art in North America. The panels are remarkably well-preserved, the trail is free to walk, and the morning light on the canyon walls is genuinely spectacular.</p>
    <ul class="feat-list">
      <li>Red Fleet dinosaur tracksite — 200+ tracks visible</li>
      <li>Reservoir swimming, kayaking, and paddleboarding</li>
      <li>Red-rock hiking trails with canyon views</li>
      <li>McConkie Ranch — free petroglyph trail, no fee</li>
      <li>Fremont-era rock art panels — some of the best in the West</li>
      <li>Photography — dramatic canyon light at sunrise and sunset</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- DOWNTOWN VERNAL -->
  <section class="content-section rv">
    <h2>Downtown Vernal — Museums, Dining &amp; Local Life</h2>
    <p>Vernal's downtown is small, friendly, and genuinely worth an afternoon. The <strong>Utah Field House of Natural History State Park Museum</strong> is the centerpiece — world-class dinosaur exhibits, a sculpture garden with life-size replicas out front, and fossil displays that rival much larger institutions. It is five minutes from the hotel and well worth the admission.</p>
    <p>Beyond the museum, Vernal has solid local restaurants, coffee shops, outdoor gear shops, and a real small-town character that most visitors find refreshing after a day in the canyons.</p>
    <div class="attraction-cards">
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>🏛️ Utah Field House Museum</strong>
        <p>World-class dinosaur exhibits and a sculpture garden with life-size replicas. Right in downtown Vernal — 5 minutes from the hotel.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>⛳ Dinaland Golf Course</strong>
        <p>18-hole public course with mountain views, just minutes from the hotel. One of the most scenic rounds in northeastern Utah.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>🌊 Steinaker State Park</strong>
        <p>Quiet reservoir park 7 miles north of Vernal — swimming, fishing, and camping with far fewer crowds than Red Fleet.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="attr-card">
        <strong>🛍️ Main Street Vernal</strong>
        <p>Western wear, outdoor gear, local art, and dinosaur souvenirs. A genuine small-town Main Street worth a slow walk.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHY STAY IN VERNAL -->
  <section class="content-section rv">
    <h2>Why Vernal Is the Best Base for All of This</h2>
    <p>Lodging options near Dinosaur National Monument, Flaming Gorge, and Red Fleet State Park are extremely limited — most visitors who try to stay closer end up driving further or paying significantly more. Vernal puts you within 20 to 40 minutes of every major attraction in the region, with full hotel amenities, restaurants, and services that simply do not exist closer to the parks.</p>
    <p>At Best Western Vernal Inn, you get a free hot breakfast every morning before you head out, free parking for trucks and trailers, fast WiFi to plan your next day, and a comfortable room to come back to after a long day on the trails.</p>
    <ul class="feat-list">
      <li>Free hot breakfast — fuel up before every adventure</li>
      <li>Free parking — trucks, trailers, and tow vehicles welcome</li>
      <li>Full kitchenettes — pack your own lunch and save</li>
      <li>Pet friendly — bring the dog on the trail</li>
      <li>Weekly rates from $588 — stay longer, spend less</li>
      <li>24-hour front desk — local knowledge always available</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="pro-tip">
      <p><strong>Local tip:</strong> Driving to Flaming Gorge? Take <strong>US-191 south</strong> from Vernal — the Flaming Gorge–Uintas National Scenic Byway. The drive through the canyon is one of the most dramatic in Utah and worth slowing down for.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

</div>

